# Node + TypeScript Backend Rule

Use this rule for backend APIs, workers, and domain logic.

## TypeScript Strictness

- Prefer `strict`-friendly patterns; never silence errors without explanation.
- Avoid `any`; prefer `unknown` + narrowing.
- Use branded/discriminated types for domain states and IDs.
- Export reusable DTO and domain types from dedicated modules.
- Use `satisfies` for object literals that must match interfaces.

## Backend Structure

- Keep transport concerns (HTTP context, status codes) out of business logic.
- Place use-case logic in services; keep controllers thin.
- Use repository/gateway interfaces to decouple storage/integrations.
- Inject dependencies explicitly to simplify testing/mocking.

## Data and Validation

- Validate and parse all inbound data using schemas (e.g. Zod/Valibot/Joi).
- Normalize outbound responses to stable contract shapes.
- Enforce pagination and filtering limits on list endpoints.
- Prefer explicit nullability over ambiguous optional fields.

## Error Handling

- Define typed domain/application errors with stable error codes.
- Map domain errors to transport-layer status codes in one place.
- Never expose stack traces or internals to external clients.
- Ensure unhandled rejection and uncaught exception hooks are configured safely.

## Async and Concurrency

- Use `await` consistently; avoid orphaned promises.
- Use `Promise.all` only for truly independent operations.
- Add concurrency limits for fan-out workloads.
- Use abort signals/timeouts for external calls.

## Performance and Runtime

- Cache read-heavy stable data where appropriate.
- Avoid blocking CPU work on the event loop; offload if needed.
- Stream large payloads when possible instead of buffering.
- Reuse clients/connections; do not recreate per request.

